Questions.correct_ans_explanation:
The method to receive the number of elements in an ArrayList is size(). However, since the elements in ArrayLists start at index 0, there is no element at index list.size(). Therefore, the expressions:

Person p = list.get(list.size());
and
Person p = list.remove(list.size());
and
for (int j = 0; j <= list.size(); j++)
        list.set(j, new Person());

ask for the index list.size(), which will cause an IndexOutOfBoundsException. Nevertheless, the expression:

list.add(list.size(), new Person()); 

doesn’t cause this exception because the .add() method allows the programmer to add a new element at the last index + 1. The AP often likes to test students on the functionality of this method.

