Questions.correct_ans_explanation:
Firstly, since j must be an integer value (because j is an index), it must be type cast into an int. Furthermore, the Math.random() function takes a random number from 0 to 1 (excluding 1). Therefore, if you multiply Math.random() by response.length, you will receive a random integer from 0 to response.length excluding response.length, which is exactly what u want for the index range. hence, the correct answer is:

int j = (int) (Math.random() * response.length);       
return response[j];

Questions.wrong_ans_explanation:
Firstly, since j must be an integer value (because j is an index), it must be type cast into an int. Furthermore, the Math.random() function takes a random number from 0 to 1 (excluding 1). Therefore, if you multiply Math.random() by response.length, you will receive a random integer from 0 to response.length excluding response.length, which is exactly what u want for the index range. hence, the correct answer is:

int j = (int) (Math.random() * response.length);       
return response[j];

